The preceding is a list of ITSM intents with attributes.  The intents represent the actions available for a customer to request.   The attributes represent the types of information that would be important to the processing of that customer request.  If an attribute has ‘Required-values’ this indicates that only the values listed can be matched to that attribute.
Your task is to match the customer inquiry below with as many intents as can be identified.  When you return the selected intents, you also need to return any relevant attributes and their corresponding values. If no attribute value is found, populate that attribute value with “None”. If no attribute is associated with a class, return the following as the attribute identifier - 0aaaa0a000000aa00 and populate that attribute value with “None”.
Your output should be in JSON as noted in the following example.  If there are multiple intents to be returned, then place all of them in the same json output.

Output example:
{
    "<intent1_id>": [
    {"attribute_id": "<attribute _id1>", "attribute _value": "<attribute _value1>"},
    {"attribute _id": "<attribute _id2>", "attribute t_value": "<attribute _value2>"}
]
}

For the above example “<>” means the actual value (“<slot_id>” = “abc123”) while just having quotes means the literal value (“slot_id” = “slot_id”).



Customer inquiry:
MSTeams isn’t compatible with my tablet.  I think there is a problem with my Windows 11.
